    "### Annual vs. Semi-Annual Coupon Payments\n",
    "\n",
    "The `coupon_frequency` parameter is crucial. Most government and corporate bonds pay coupons semi-annually. \n",
    "\n",
    "*   **Semi-Annual Payments:** The annual coupon rate and annual market yield are divided by 2 to get per-period values. The number of periods is `Years to Maturity * 2`.\n",
    "*   **Annual Payments:** The annual rates are used directly, and the number of periods equals `Years to Maturity`.\n",
    "\n",
    "Holding all else equal, a bond paying semi-annually will have a slightly higher price than an identical bond paying annually if priced at the same *annual* market yield. This is because the investor receives some cash flows sooner, and these can be reinvested earlier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Pull to Par\n",
    "\n",
    "\"Pull to par\" refers to the tendency of a bond's price to converge towards its par value as its maturity date approaches, assuming no default by the issuer. \n",
    "\n",
    "*   If a bond is trading at a **discount** (price < par value), its price will gradually increase towards par as maturity nears.\n",
    "*   If a bond is trading at a **premium** (price > par value), its price will gradually decrease towards par as maturity nears.\n",
    "\n",
    "This happens because at maturity, the bondholder will receive the par value. As that date gets closer, the remaining coupon payments have less influence on the price compared to the final par value repayment.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's visualize this:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_pull_to_par(par_value, annual_coupon_rate, initial_years_to_maturity, annual_market_yield, coupon_frequency):\n",
    "    time_to_maturity = np.arange(initial_years_to_maturity, -1/coupon_frequency, -1/coupon_frequency) # Go down to 0\n",
    "    # Ensure we don't pass negative years to maturity for the last step if it's exactly 0\n",
    "    time_to_maturity = np.maximum(time_to_maturity, 0) \n",
    "    \n",
    "    prices = [calculate_bond_price(par_value, annual_coupon_rate, ttm, annual_market_yield, coupon_frequency) \n",
    "              if ttm > 0 else par_value \n",
    "              for ttm in time_to_maturity]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "    plt.plot(time_to_maturity, prices, marker='o', linestyle='-')\n",
    "    plt.axhline(par_value, color='grey', linestyle='--', label=f'Par Value (${par_value:,.0f})')\n",
    "    plt.title(f'Pull to Par (Coupon: {annual_coupon_rate}%, Market Yield: {annual_market_yield}%)')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Years to Maturity')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Bond Price ($)')\n",
    "    plt.gca().invert_xaxis() # Time decreases towards maturity\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "    plt.grid(True)\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Interactive Pull to Par Demo\n",
    "pull_par_value_widget = FloatSlider(value=1000, min=100, max=10000, step=100, description='Par Value ($):', readout_format='$,.0f', layout={'width': '500px'})\n",
    "pull_coupon_rate_widget = FloatSlider(value=6, min=0, max=20, step=0.1, description='Coupon Rate (%):', readout_format='.1f', layout={'width': '500px'})\n",
