    "## (Optional) Section 6: Impact of Embedded Options\n",
    "\n",
    "Many bonds contain embedded options, which grant either the issuer or the bondholder the right to take a specific action at some point in the future. These options significantly affect a bond's risk and return characteristics, including its price sensitivity to interest rates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Callable Bonds\n",
    "\n",
    "A **callable bond** gives the *issuer* the right, but not the obligation, to redeem (or \"call\") the bond before its scheduled maturity date at a specified call price. \n",
    "\n",
    "*   **Why issue?** Issuers typically call bonds when interest rates have fallen significantly since the bond was issued. They can then re-issue debt at the new, lower interest rate, reducing their borrowing costs.\n",
    "*   **Impact on Bondholder:** Callable bonds are less attractive to bondholders than otherwise identical non-callable bonds because:\n",
    "    *   **Reinvestment Risk:** If the bond is called, the investor receives their principal back earlier than expected and must reinvest it, likely at lower prevailing interest rates.\n",
    "    *   **Price Capping (Negative Convexity):** As interest rates fall, the price of a callable bond will not rise as much as a non-callable bond. The price tends to be capped near the call price because investors anticipate the bond will be called. This phenomenon is often referred to as **negative convexity** at low yield levels. The price-yield curve for a callable bond becomes flatter and may even curve downwards at low yields.\n",
    "\n",
    "The value of a callable bond can be thought of as:\n",
    "$$ \\text{Value of Callable Bond} = \\text{Value of Option-Free Bond} - \\text{Value of Call Option} $$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Putable Bonds\n",
    "\n",
    "A **putable bond** (or put bond) gives the *bondholder* the right, but not the obligation, to sell the bond back to the issuer before its maturity date at a specified put price on predetermined dates.\n",
    "\n",
    "*   **Why valuable to bondholder?** Bondholders typically exercise the put option when interest rates have risen significantly since the bond was issued. This allows them to get their principal back and reinvest at higher prevailing rates.\n",
    "*   **Impact on Bondholder:** Putable bonds are more attractive to bondholders than otherwise identical non-putable bonds because:\n",
    "    *   **Protection Against Rising Rates:** The put option provides a floor for the bond's price. As interest rates rise and the bond's price would normally fall, the ability to sell it back at the put price limits the downside risk.\n",
    "    *   **Price Floor Effect:** The price of a putable bond will not fall as much as a non-putable bond when interest rates rise. The price tends to be supported near the put price.\n",
    "\n",
    "The value of a putable bond can be thought of as:\n",
    "$$ \\text{Value of Putable Bond} = \\text{Value of Option-Free Bond} + \\text{Value of Put Option} $$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Option-Adjusted Spread (OAS)\n",
    "\n",
    "When valuing bonds with embedded options, the standard Yield-to-Maturity (YTM) can be misleading because it doesn't account for the possibility of early redemption or sale.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **Option-Adjusted Spread (OAS)** is a more appropriate measure. It is the constant spread that, when added to all the one-period forward rates on the benchmark yield curve (e.g., government bond curve), makes the theoretical price of the bond (calculated using a model that incorporates the option) equal to its current market price.\n",
    "\n",
    "*   A **higher OAS** generally implies a cheaper bond, after adjusting for the option's value.\n",
    "*   Calculating OAS typically involves complex interest rate models (e.g., binomial trees) to value the embedded option under various interest rate scenarios.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook does not delve into OAS calculations due to their complexity, but it's an important concept to be aware of when dealing with callable or putable bonds."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Summary of Impact on Price-Yield Relationship\n",
    "\n",
    "*   **Callable Bonds:** Exhibit *negative convexity* when yields are low (prices are high, near the call price). The price appreciation is limited.\n",
    "*   **Putable Bonds:** Provide a *price floor*, limiting downside price risk when yields rise.\n",
    "\n",
    "Understanding these dynamics is crucial for accurately assessing the risk and reward of bonds with embedded options."
   ]
  },
